Electricty Imbalance Cost Distribution Across Months in Turkey

Enes Özeren

6/20/2019

ELECTRICITY MARKET IN TURKEY

Electricity Market is the platform for trading and dealing on prices of electricity for Companies which buy/sell electricity. EPIAS is the operator of Electricity Market in Turkey. This market is mainly formed as a result of heavy cost of electrical energy storage. On the other hand, there are some restrictions about production, electric power transmission, and electricity distribution. Consequently, the Market for Electricity should be performed consistently and carefully.

ELECTRICITY MARKET PRICES

In day-ahead market (GÖP in Turkish) the prices for the next day are determined as a result of matching-ups. This price is called PTF in Turkish which stands for market clearing price (MCP). However, most of the time there are differences in production/consumption values between intended and real time. To close the gap between these differences, Balancing Market (DGP) and Intra-day Market (GİP in Turkish) is developed. The prices in Intra-Day Market is called System Marginal Price (SMF in Turkish). For more information about Markets and Prices visit https://www.epias.com.tr/ .

COST of IMBALANCES in ELECTRICTY

From the difference in MCP and SMP, a cost for companies occurs. The cost is specified according to Positive and Negative Imbalance. Positive Imbalance is result of Electrical Energy Surplus of a company, while Negative Imbalance is result of Electrical Energy Deficit.
A company that has energy surplus can sell electricity to another company in Intra-day Market with MCP. However, a %3 fine is imposed for that trade for that company. This fine can be called as Positive Cost for the company. On the other hand, a company which has energy deficit can buy electricity from another company with SMP. A fine of %3 is imposed on SMP for that company as well. So, the cost from the difference of SMP and MCP and %3 fine can be called as Negative Cost. 
In this project, we will analyze the changes of Positive and Negative Costs in Turkey Electricity Market by month.

AIM By analyzing the data, our aim is to visualize the cost of the Imbalances in the Market with respect to months.

DATA SOURCE and TIME INTERVAL Data used in this project is imported from EPIAS Transparency Platform. Data imported for the analysis is dated between 01-01-2015 00:00 and 31-05-2019 23:00 to have a better understanding of costs in Turkish currency.

#PTF - SMF TOGETHER

PTF_SMF = read.csv("ptf-smf.csv", fileEncoding = "latin1")

Rearrange the names of Columns

names(PTF_SMF)[names(PTF_SMF) == "Tarih"] <- "Date"
names(PTF_SMF)[names(PTF_SMF) == "Pozitif.Dengesizlik.Fiyatý..TL.MWh."] <- "Positive_Imbalance_Price(TL/MWh)"
names(PTF_SMF)[names(PTF_SMF) == "Negatif.Dengesizlik.Fiyatý..TL.MWh."] <- "Negative_Imbalance_Price(TL/MWh)"
names(PTF_SMF)[names(PTF_SMF) == "SMF.Yön"] <- "SMF_Direction"
setDT(PTF_SMF)
PTF_SMF[,SMF_Direction:=ifelse(SMF_Direction=="? Enerji Açýðý", "Energy Deficit", 
                               ifelse(SMF_Direction=="?Enerji Fazlasý", "Energy Surplus", "Balanced"))]

Correction of Data Types

PTF_SMF[, Date:=parse_date_time(Date, "dmy HM")]

PTF_SMF$PTF <- gsub(",", "", as.character(PTF_SMF$PTF), fixed = TRUE)
PTF_SMF$PTF <- as.numeric(PTF_SMF$PTF)
PTF_SMF$PTF <- PTF_SMF$PTF/100
PTF_SMF$SMF <- gsub(",", "", as.character(PTF_SMF$SMF), fixed = TRUE)
PTF_SMF$SMF <- as.numeric(PTF_SMF$SMF)
PTF_SMF$SMF <- PTF_SMF$SMF/100
PTF_SMF$`Positive_Imbalance_Price(TL/MWh)` <- gsub(",", "", as.character(PTF_SMF$`Positive_Imbalance_Price(TL/MWh)`), fixed = TRUE)
PTF_SMF$`Positive_Imbalance_Price(TL/MWh)` <- as.numeric(PTF_SMF$`Positive_Imbalance_Price(TL/MWh)`)
PTF_SMF$`Positive_Imbalance_Price(TL/MWh)` <- PTF_SMF$`Positive_Imbalance_Price(TL/MWh)`/100
PTF_SMF$`Negative_Imbalance_Price(TL/MWh)` <- gsub(",", "", as.character(PTF_SMF$`Negative_Imbalance_Price(TL/MWh)`), fixed = TRUE)
PTF_SMF$`Negative_Imbalance_Price(TL/MWh)` <- as.numeric(PTF_SMF$`Negative_Imbalance_Price(TL/MWh)`)
PTF_SMF$`Negative_Imbalance_Price(TL/MWh)` <- PTF_SMF$`Negative_Imbalance_Price(TL/MWh)`/100

Lets check MCP and SMP graphs

plot(PTF_SMF$Date, PTF_SMF$PTF, xlab = "Date", ylab = "PTF(MCP) (TL)", main = "Daily PTF(MCP)")

plot(PTF_SMF$Date, PTF_SMF$SMF, xlab = "Date", ylab = "SMF(SMP) (TL)", main = "Daily SMF(SMP)")

We can see the outliers in 2016-12-23. The reason for those prices was an energy crisis in Turkey. It was related with natural gas usage and production of electricty.

#Improving data by replacing outliers with median
Interval_2016_December <- PTF_SMF[Date >"2016-12-01 00:00" & Date < "2017-01-01 00:00"]
median(Interval_2016_December$PTF)

median(Interval_2016_December$SMF)

PTF_SMF[, PTF:=ifelse(PTF > 599, median(Interval_2016_December$PTF), PTF)]
PTF_SMF[, SMF:=ifelse(SMF > 599, median(Interval_2016_December$SMF), SMF)]

Now we have a better data for analysis.

Calculating Costs in Positive Imbalance(Energy Surplus) and costs in Negative Imbalance(Energy Deficit) cases

PTF_SMF[, Positive_Cost:= PTF-`Positive_Imbalance_Price(TL/MWh)`]
PTF_SMF[, Negative_Cost:=`Negative_Imbalance_Price(TL/MWh)`-PTF]

Now let’s see Monthly Average Total Costs

plot(Monthly_Average_of_Total_Cost$Date, Monthly_Average_of_Total_Cost$Total_Cost, xlab = "Date",
     ylab = "Cost (TL)", main = "Monthly Average Costs", type = "b")

To have a clear vision, let’s calculate the mean of Total Cost for months.

Temp <- copy(Monthly_Average_of_Total_Cost)
General_Average <- aggregate(Total_Cost~  Month, Temp, mean)
names(General_Average)[names(General_Average)=="Total_Cost"] <- "Average_Daily_Cost"

plot(General_Average$Month, General_Average$Average_Daily_Cost, type = "b",
     xlab = "Month", ylab = "Cost (TL)", main = "Average Cost for Months between 01-01-2015 and 31-05-2019")

Result from our final graph:

The table shows the average daily costs for each month. From this plot, we can see that the Electricty Imbalance Costs for Companies have the lowest level in February-March (Begenning of spring season) and October-November(End of fall season). On the other hand, The Costs are in the highest level in December-January(Winter season), April-May(Spring season) and September(fall season).

CONCLUSION

Overall, for last 4 and a half year, companies had a cost about 93547 TL in a day in December month on average. So, december is the most costly month for the companies while they had a cost about 55674 TL in a day in August which is the lowest costly month.
